{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-blog-template-js","path":"/blog/castellated-vias.html","result":{"data":{"markdownRemark":{"html":"<p>Today I'm thinking about the best way to stack boards (to support extensions in other words). In my search I <a href=\"https://hallmanlabs.com/2020/07/20/discrete-review-update-isoregen-over-troubled-dip8-waters/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">stumbled upon</a> these DIP adapters</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 650px; flex:1.1013513513513513;\"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/caea80903d2c4f6256079d36f0d6fcdf/92f8c/dip-stacking.webp\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 90.79754601226993%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/webp;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"DIP adapters\"\n        title=\"\"\n        src=\"/static/caea80903d2c4f6256079d36f0d6fcdf/c1dc5/dip-stacking.webp\"\n        srcset=\"/static/caea80903d2c4f6256079d36f0d6fcdf/94563/dip-stacking.webp 163w,\n/static/caea80903d2c4f6256079d36f0d6fcdf/647a8/dip-stacking.webp 325w,\n/static/caea80903d2c4f6256079d36f0d6fcdf/c1dc5/dip-stacking.webp 650w,\n/static/caea80903d2c4f6256079d36f0d6fcdf/1e975/dip-stacking.webp 975w,\n/static/caea80903d2c4f6256079d36f0d6fcdf/92f8c/dip-stacking.webp 1200w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 650px) 100vw, 650px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n        decoding=\"async\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<p>I find Arduino shields bulky. And they can only grow upwards. I want to have flexibility in this regard.</p>\n<p>There's such technique as \"<a href=\"https://learn.sparkfun.com/tutorials/how-to-solder-castellated-mounting-holes/all\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">castellated vias</a>\" where connections are on the edge of the board. Like through holes that metallized inside but located on the edge and cut in half</p>\n<p>First I shook off this idea, because it's used mainly for adding daughter boards, so I was considering pinheads. But they restrict the direction of attachments—it only goes in the way it's designed to go.</p>\n<p>But then I revisited initial limitations, and soldering wasn't in the list. The credit goes to <a href=\"https://jeremyscook.com/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Jeremy Cook</a> and his <a href=\"https://hackaday.com/2022/03/15/led-flower-bouquet-is-a-radiant-hacker-desk-decoration/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">LED cubes</a></p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 650px; flex:1.4954128440366972;\"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/bcf60b2685349cdbdd638ecd545022a4/0f98f/cube-of-pcbs.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 66.87116564417178%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Cube of PCBs\"\n        title=\"\"\n        src=\"/static/bcf60b2685349cdbdd638ecd545022a4/6aca1/cube-of-pcbs.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/static/bcf60b2685349cdbdd638ecd545022a4/d2f63/cube-of-pcbs.jpg 163w,\n/static/bcf60b2685349cdbdd638ecd545022a4/c989d/cube-of-pcbs.jpg 325w,\n/static/bcf60b2685349cdbdd638ecd545022a4/6aca1/cube-of-pcbs.jpg 650w,\n/static/bcf60b2685349cdbdd638ecd545022a4/7c09c/cube-of-pcbs.jpg 975w,\n/static/bcf60b2685349cdbdd638ecd545022a4/01ab0/cube-of-pcbs.jpg 1300w,\n/static/bcf60b2685349cdbdd638ecd545022a4/0f98f/cube-of-pcbs.jpg 1920w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 650px) 100vw, 650px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n        decoding=\"async\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<p>I'm thinking about an extension board for 2 more bi-directional motors. I put one full row of vias on the edge and get castellated edge (I do the bottom row as well). OSH Park <a href=\"https://docs.oshpark.com/tips+tricks/castellation/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">can manufacture such edge</a> but with possible imperfections</p>","excerpt":"Today I'm thinking about the best way to stack boards (to support extensions in other words). In my search I stumbled upon these DIP…","tableOfContents":"","frontmatter":{"date":"December 16, 2022","published":"December 20, 2022","lastModified":"December 20, 2022","title":"Castellated vias","subtitle":"As the way to \"stack\" extension boards","section":null,"draft":null,"developing":null,"buttonText":null,"buttonLink":null,"secondButtonText":null,"secondButtonLink":null,"featuredImage":null}}},"pageContext":{"showLikes":true,"absolutePath":"/home/runner/work/mikolasan.github.io/mikolasan.github.io/src/markdown/blog/castellated-vias.md","url":"/blog/castellated-vias","next":{"excerpt":"Sometimes using  on Linux you can get a long traceback message instead of a plot that you expected.\nStrangely it says something about key…","fileAbsolutePath":"/home/runner/work/mikolasan.github.io/mikolasan.github.io/src/markdown/blog/matplotlib-on-linux.md","frontmatter":{"title":"Matplotlib on linux","date":"2023-01-27T00:00:00.000Z","topic":null,"article":null},"id":"44a02b53-1fa9-5d03-9329-71178d64ea4a"},"previous":{"excerpt":"If you wonder about the  registe